<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance was cited as <i>Bromus tectorum </i>Semi-Natural Herbaceous Stands in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>.  The alliance has been expanded to include stands dominated by other invasive exotic annual grasses of the Great Basin ecoregion section such as   <i>Taeniatherum caput-medusae </i>. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Bromus tectorum </i>is a non-native, annual grass that is favored by cultivation, frequent fire, and overgrazing. Plants grow as long as soil moisture is present, commonly maturing, fruiting, and drying by late June. As the plants mature and cure, they change from bright green to red-purple to straw. Seeds accumulate in the litter from earlier plants. Moist litter offers perfect conditions for seed germination. Seeds germinate in the fall, if water is available, and seedlings grow until temperatures drop; seeds may germinate in the spring and even in summer. Plant production varies among years depending on seasonal precipitation and temperature patterns (Carpenter and Murray 2005, DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Young 2000, Zouhar 2003a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Bromus tectorum </i>seriously impacts natural vegetation in northeastern California and invades other middle elevation sites in California, especially post-burn areas adjacent to woodlands. Rarely have regional vegetation patterns been as rapidly changed as with the spread of <i>B. tectorum </i>in the intermountain West (Upadhyaya et al. 1986). <i>B. tectorum </i>competes well with other plants for soil moisture and then promotes frequent fires. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
