    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Bromus tectorum</i> is statewide.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-f, Ah-n, Ap-r, Au). Stands in Castle Crags State Park (Stuart et al. 1993) occur in forest openings.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-p). <i>B. tectorum </i>is a major component of many regional vegetation types in this section, including the <i>Juniperus occidentalis </i>and <i>Artemisia arbuscula </i>alliances. It also regularly dominates immediately following fires in these settings. Stands mapped at Pine and Fitzhugh Creek wildlife areas appear less troublesome than stands of <i>Taeniatherum caput-medusae </i>or <i>Ventenata dubia </i>(Hickson et al. 2008).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341D). Sands occur after fire in areas formerly dominated by <i>Artemisia tridentata, Pinus jeffreyi, </i>or <i>P. monophylla.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-n, Ep-u). Stands are dominant for at least a few years following fire in <i>P. monophylla </i>stands in the eastern portions of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). <i>B. tectorum </i>dominates grasslands at higher elevations of Anza-Borrego Desert State Park with <i>B. diandrus </i>(Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b). Similarly, stands in the Cleghorn Canyon RNA in San Bernardino Co. (White 1994a) contain <i>B. diandrus</i>. Stands at San Felipe Valley and Volcan Mountain in San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) contain <i>B. rubens </i>and sometimes emergent <i>P. coulteri </i>trees. Stands also occur at middle elevations of western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005). These contain <i>B. rubens, Croton setigerus, Hirschfeldia incana, </i>or emergent <i>Pinus jeffreyi </i>trees.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-m). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Native species may persist in areas with <i>Bromus tectorum </i>dominance, so control must consider the natives in restoration plans (Young 2000). Carpenter and Murray (2005) recommended a combination of chemical and physical control using fire and other methods, and proper livestock management on ranges. This approach provides a level of redundancy when one method is ineffective. Jimerson et al. (2000) advised multiple treatments: fall burning to expose soil and destroy the seed bank, grazing at times when seed heads are just developing and green, and reseeding with native plants. </div>
</div>

    

    

